Dear Hiring Team, 

It is with great pleasure that I submit my candidacy for the Software Engineer position with Trimble. I bring over three years of professional experience in full-stack development, security-focused backend systems, and Identity & Access Management, along with a strong academic foundation as a Master of Science in Computer Science graduate from Pace University, NY.

Through my experience across two engineering roles, I have built and delivered production-grade systems that directly reflect the FedRAMP certification requirements and security-first engineering this position demands. As a Software Engineer at Sperse, I architected a secure API validation layer that translates natural-language intents into validated, auditable tool calls across 1,000+ endpoints — requiring rigorous input sanitization, authorization checks, and comprehensive audit logging for compliance. To ensure production readiness and security monitoring, I built observability infrastructure using Langfuse and LangSmith with structured logging, distributed tracing, and real-time alerting to detect security anomalies and maintain audit trails. I also implemented system hardening across multi-agent orchestration, enforcing least-privilege access, rate limiting, and secure credential management — all critical components of FedRAMP security controls. Additionally, I developed technical documentation covering API contracts, security controls, deployment procedures, and operational runbooks for audit-ready compliance verification. Prior to Sperse, as a Software Engineer at Qualitest, I contributed directly to an Identity & Access Management platform built with React, Spring Boot, and AWS, implementing authentication, authorization, and role-based access controls for thousands of users across 30+ applications. I also designed a cloud-agnostic Storage Service using Python, PostgreSQL, and Redis with secure signed URLs, encryption at rest, and audit logging across Google Cloud Storage, S3, and MinIO — giving me hands-on experience with secure cloud-native architectures and compliance-focused design. Together, these roles have prepared me to contribute meaningfully to Trimble's FedRAMP certification effort, driving code refactoring, security control implementation, and enhanced monitoring capabilities within an agile engineering team.

My academic research experience has given me a rigorous foundation in secure system design, technical documentation, and knowledge sharing — skills that translate directly into the engineering discipline and collaborative culture Trimble values. As an AI Researcher at the Pace Artificial Intelligence Lab, I conducted applied research on StyleGAN and Stable Diffusion, implementing secure model training workflows with access controls and audit logging on Pace University's HPC cluster. I deployed models using vLLM and Hugging Face with security-hardened configurations, ensuring encrypted transmission and secure serving endpoints. Beyond building the systems myself, I led workshops on GPU programming with CUDA and Mojo, and on building AI Agents with LangChain and LangGraph, for an audience of 50+ students, creating comprehensive documentation and training materials. Designing and delivering those sessions required me to break down complex technical concepts clearly and accessibly — directly mirroring the technical communication and documentation responsibilities central to FedRAMP certification. This experience has shaped me into an engineer who builds with rigor and communicates with clarity, both of which I would bring to Trimble's Identity and Access Management team.

I have always been passionate about fostering belonging and driving innovation through collaborative problem-solving, and envision myself contributing my talent to the furthering of Trimble's mission to transform the way the world works. I would love to discuss my interest in this position with your team and can be reached at #ph or #eml. Thank you for your time and consideration, I look forward to connecting!

